{"copyright": {"licenseType": "NO", "determinationType": "OTHER", "thirdPartyContentCondition": "NOT_SET"}, "subjectCategories": ["INSTRUMENTATION AND PHOTOGRAPHY"], "exportControl": {"isExportControl": "NO", "ear": "NO", "itar": "NO"}, "distributionDate": "2019-06-19T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "fundingNumbers": [{"number": "NASA ORDER W-15047", "type": "CONTRACT_GRANT"}], "title": "Tunable far-infrared spectroscopy", "stiType": "REPRINT", "distribution": "PUBLIC", "submittedDate": "2013-08-12T02:12:00.0000000+00:00", "authorAffiliations": [{"sequence": 0, "submissionId": 19840043695, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Evenson, K. M."}, "organization": {"name": "National Bureau of Standards", "location": "Boulder, CO, United States"}}, "id": "b4ea31ff6e1e4131bb39fb4db7cfefbb"}, {"sequence": 1, "submissionId": 19840043695, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Jennings, D. A."}, "organization": {"name": "National Bureau of Standards", "location": "Boulder, CO, United States"}}, "id": "e98b6b326479411e8de4d9638d4347f2"}, {"sequence": 2, "submissionId": 19840043695, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Petersen, F. R."}, "organization": {"name": "National Bureau of Standards, Time and Frequency Div., Boulder", "location": "CO, United States"}}, "id": "5f0f02859a7a4a969d1a9b3d9be082d3"}], "stiTypeDetails": "Reprint (Version printed in journal)", "technicalReviewType": "TECHNICAL_REVIEW_TYPE_NONE", "modified": "2011-08-17T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "id": 19840043695, "sourceIdentifiers": [{"number": "doi:10.1063/1.94845", "type": "DOI"}], "created": "2013-08-12T02:12:00.0000000+00:00", "center": {"code": "CDMS", "name": "Legacy CDMS", "id": "092d6e0881874968859b972d39a888dc"}, "onlyAbstract": false, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "abstract": "Tunable, CW, far-infrared radiation has been generated by nonlinear mixing of radiation from two CO2 lasers in a metal-insulator-metal (MIM) diode. The FIR difference-frequency power radiated from the MIM diode antenna to a calibrated indium antimonide bolometer. Two-tenths of a microwatt of FIR power was generated by 250 mW from each of the CO2 lasers. The combination of lines from a waveguide CO2 laser, with its larger tuning range, with lines from CO2, N2O, and CO2 isotopic lasers promises complete coverage of the entire far-infrared band from 100 to 5000 GHz (3-200 per cm) with stepwise-tunable CW radiation. To demonstrate the usefulness of the technique, the J = 4-5 line of CO was observed at 567 GHz.", "isLessonsLearned": false, "disseminated": "METADATA_ONLY", "publications": [{"volume": "44", "submissionId": 19840043695, "issn": "0003-6951", "id": "e0cbdb8453a24293bdfbce6a5b059899", "publicationName": "Applied Physics Letters", "publicationDate": "1984-03-15T00:00:00.0000000+00:00"}], "status": "CURATED", "related": [], "downloads": [], "downloadsAvailable": false, "index": "submissions-2022-09-30-06-07"}